    "client_msg_id": "81e4884e-075c-4293-8c62-59e0ca83b89d",
    "type": "message",
    "text": "I wasn't claiming that we shouldn't visualize physical objects. I was claiming that focusing on _just_ the physical is an intellectual disease. When we think of the world we mostly visualize maps. When we think of \"Steve Jobs\" we mostly visualize his body, which is why sharing the same restaurant or auditorium with it seems to become worthy of comment. But the geography of the world hides many flows that would be better off emphasized. Steve Jobs when he lived inhabited a far vaster phase space than just his body.\n\nI think you should visualize a bacterium or mitochondrion out of building blocks of flows rather than atoms. That may end up being vastly more complex or less complex, depending on the details of the flows you choose. Neither should stop you.\n\nShort story recommendation: <https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/17084967-wang-s-carpets>",
    "user": "UCUSW7WVD",
